## Main reasons for failing

* lack of documentation
* lack of time
* lack of experience on C++

We chose to use Picovoice because the wake word and speech-to-indent fuction look promising, but even it exists a Rhino speech-to-indent offical demo on cortex-m7 ([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WadKhfLyqTQ](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WadKhfLyqTQ)), there isn't documentation or support for MCU (2023-03-02). So we start with Porcupine ([https://picovoice.ai/docs/quick-start/porcupine-microcontroller/#platforms](https://picovoice.ai/docs/quick-start/porcupine-microcontroller/#platforms)).

## General ideas

1. Use Porcupine console to build voice model.
2. Use Porcupine SDK for wake word recognition.
3. Use Teensy Audio Library to record speech and pass the voice frame to Porcupine SDK.

## Build voice model with Porcupine

Go to [https://console.picovoice.ai/ppn](https://console.picovoice.ai/ppn%E2%80%B8).

Train a model on picovoice console.

Download model and get AccessKey.

Use model file .h and AccessKey in .ino file.

## Problems

Test code using Teensy Audio Library is written and ready for testing, but Porcupine SDK (not open-source) ([https://github.com/Picovoice/porcupine/tree/master/lib/mcu](https://github.com/Picovoice/porcupine/tree/master/lib/mcu)) might correspond to specific hardwares:

1. `libpv_porcupine.a` for `imxrt1050`, `stm32f769` and `Portenta H7` are different.
2. There are 2 .h files for include: `pv_porcupine.h` and `pv_porcupine_mcu.h`, `Portenta H7` uses `pv_porcupine.h` while some of the other use `pv_porcupine_mcu.h`.

## 1st method to add a pre-compiled library (Porcupine SDK)

Create a library according to the specification for the Arduino library format: [https://arduino.github.io/arduino-cli/0.31/library-specification/](https://arduino.github.io/arduino-cli/0.31/library-specification/)

ref: [https://github.com/Picovoice/porcupine-arduino-en](https://github.com/Picovoice/porcupine-arduino-en) (official library for Arduino Nano 33 BLE Sense and Arduino Portenta H7)

Create `Teensy_Picovoice` in arduino-1.8.19/libraries:

`cp libpv_porcupine.a Teensy_Picovoice/src/imxrt1062/fpv5-d16-hard`

Create `Teensy_Picovoice.cpp` and .h in `Teensy_Picovoice/src` to include:

```
#include<stdint.h>
#include"Arduino.h"
#include"pv_porcupine.h"
#include"pv_audio.h"
```

Edit `keywords.txt`
Edit `library.properties`

```
precompiled=true
ldflags=-lpv_porcupine
```

## 2nd method to add a pre-compiled library (Porcupine SDK)

ref: [https://forum.pjrc.com/threads/50172-How-to-add-a-pre-compiled-library](https://forum.pjrc.com/threads/50172-How-to-add-a-pre-compiled-library)

 **`cp libpv_porcupine.a arduino-1.8.19/hardware/tools/arm/arm-none-eabi/lib/`**

Edit hardware/teensy/avr/boards.txt for Teensy4.0 architecture

Modify line502: `teensy40.build.flags.libs=-larm_cortexM7lfsp_math -lpv_porcupine -lm -lstdc++`

NB:

* re-do this every time you upgrade IDE.
* suboptimal since from now `libpv_porcupine` is linked into every teensy4.0 project.
